entities.name: Quickstart
entities.description: Unleash your SAPUI5 skills with this simple three step tutorial.

entities.name: Walkthrough
entities.description: In this tutorial we are introducing you to all major development paradigms of SAPUI5.

entities.name: Testing
entities.description: In this tutorial we will test application functionality with QUnit, OPA5, and the mock server.

Writing a Short Date Formatter Using TDD

entities.name: Worklist App
entities.description: In this tutorial we implement typical features of a full-screen worklist app, a typical SAP Fiori design pattern.

samples.name: News Content
samples.description: This control is used to display the news content text and subheader in a tile.

samples.name: Message Page
samples.description: This sample displays the MessagePage with basic information.

samples.name: Message Page With FormattedText and Buttons
samples.description: This sample displays the MessagePage with FormattedText and buttons.

samples.name: Combo box
samples.description: The combo box control provides a list box with items and a text field allowing the user to either type a value directly into the control or choose from the list of existing items.

samples.name: Combo box with value state
samples.description: The combo box can show different value states.

samples.name: Combo box - Two columns layout
samples.description: Use the combo box dropdown list with two columns layout if you need to display additional information to your options, like e.g. currencies to countries or abbreviations to systems.

samples.name: Combo box - Lazy loading
samples.description: Use this feature to defer initialization of items until the point at which the items are needed. It can improve performance, reduce memory usage and unnecessary client/server round-trips.

samples.name: Combo box - Search in both columns
samples.description: Combo box dropdown list with search functionality which checks both columns. When you need to display additional information on your options, like e.g. keys of countries or system abbreviations, and want to search in those as well.

samples.name: Combo box - Default Filtering
samples.description: The default filtering is 'starts with per term', which filters by the beginning of every word in every column. Autocomplete (type-ahead) works only for the first column, the leading value.

samples.name: Combo box - Custom filtering "Contains"
samples.description: You can override the default filtering "Starts with per term" with your own filter function using the setFilterFunction method. The "Contains" approach searches everywhere in the entries.

samples.name: Combo box - Custom filtering "Starts with"
samples.description: You can override the default filtering "Starts with per term" with your own filter function using the setFilterFunction method. The "Starts with" approach searches only in the beginning of the entries in both columns.

samples.name: ComboBox - Grouping of items
samples.description: Items in the ComboBox could be grouped by a property

samples.name: ComboBox - Validation
samples.description: The combo box control could be restricted to allow selection only from the items in the list.

samples.name: Date Range Selection
samples.description: The Date Range Selection is an extension of the Date Picker Control and enables the user to select range of dates.

samples.name: Toolbar vs Bar vs OverflowToolbar
samples.description: Toolbar handles overflow by shrinking items. OverflowToolbar provides an overflow menu. Bar is able to perfectly center a text if nothing overflows.

samples.name: QuickView
samples.description: QuickView embedded in popover

samples.name: QuickView with navigation and data binding
samples.description: QuickView using navOrigin parameter when navigating

samples.name: QuickView with fallback icon
samples.description: QuickView using a fallback icon when there are problems with loading.

samples.name: QuickViewCard
samples.description: QuickView embedded in container

samples.name: QuickViewCard - Scroll example
samples.description: QuickView embedded in container with scroll bar

samples.name: Responsive Popover
samples.description: The Responsive Popover is an abstraction of Popover and Dialog. On the phone a Dialog will be shown. On tablet and desktop a Popover is shown.

samples.name: Responsive Refresh
samples.description: An 'Responsive Refresh' can be achieved by the combination of a Search Field's refresh button and a Pull To Refresh, both of which appear depending on whether the device is touch-enabled. A growing stream of backend data is simulated here.

samples.name: Table - Columns
samples.description: The table shares many features with the list and, in addition, introduces columns. The table is fully responsive and can hide columns or shown them in-place if the screen space is not sufficient. This example also demonstrates the different table pop-in layout options along with sticky column headers, header toolbar and info toolbar options.

samples.name: Table Test with OPA
samples.description: The following example simulates a click on a list item in a table.

samples.name: Action Sheet
samples.description: Action Sheet provides an easier way of showing a list of actions and allowing the user to select one. Title and cancel buttons can be shown or hidden. Without an icon the entry will still be aligned (see the last action in the list).

samples.name: Button
samples.description: Buttons trigger user actions and come in a variety of shapes and colors. Placing a button on a page header or footer changes its appearance.

samples.name: Toggle Button
samples.description: Toggle Buttons can be toggled between pressed and normal state.

samples.name: OverflowToolbar - Alignment
samples.description: OverflowToolbar and Toolbar are often used for left/right alignment. This is easily achieved with ToolbarSpacer.

samples.name: OverflowToolbar - Active
samples.description: Making an OverflowToolbar or a Toolbar active allows them to react to the click event.

samples.name: OverflowToolbar - Enabled
samples.description: The Enabled property can be used to enable or disable all the controls inside the OverflowToolbar/Toolbar.

samples.name: OverflowToolbar - Design and styling
samples.description: The Design and Style properties can be used to specify the visual design of the OverflowToolbar/Toolbar.

samples.name: Toolbar - Shrinkable items
samples.description: Toolbar items can shrink/expand when the toolbar is resized. This behavior is enabled/disabled via the ToolbarLayoutData layout. It is also possible to set min/max width for shrinkable items.

samples.name: Link
samples.description: Here are some links. Typically links are used in user interfaces to trigger navigation to related content inside or outside of the current application.

samples.name: Link - Subtle
samples.description: Subtle links should be used to indicate less important links in tables with a large number of links. In this example all columns contain links, only the first column is non-subtle.

samples.name: Link - Emphasized
samples.description: Usually you use an Object Identifier in the first column of a table. But if you need an active identifier you should use an 'emphasized' link instead.

samples.name: LightBox
samples.description: Displays several image thumbnails. Clicking on each of them will open a LightBox.

samples.name: URL Helper
samples.description: The URL Helper can be used to easily trigger a phone's native apps like Email, Telephone and SMS. It can be used with any UI control but typically an active Display List Item is chosen.

samples.name: Pull To Refresh
samples.description: With the Pull to Refresh you can trigger an update operation by swiping the current page down on touch devices. On other devices the Pull To Refresh is visible all the time and the user clicks it like a button.

samples.name: Carousel
samples.description: A sample of a Carousel that contains images.

samples.name: Carousel With Controls
samples.description: With the Carousel a user can browse through multi-page content by swiping left or right.

samples.name: Carousel With Display Options
samples.description: The Carousel have options for the arrows placement, page indicator placement and page indicator visibility.

samples.name: Carousel with Multiple Items at Once
samples.description: The customLayout aggregation determines how many pages are displayed in Carousel's visible area.

samples.name: Comparison Pattern
samples.description: The pattern allows users to select multiple items from an sap.m.Table and display information about them in a structured way - all items are displayed next to each other for easy comparison, based on their specifics.

samples.name: Nav Container
samples.description: The Nav Container stacks multiple pages and offers an API to switch between them with some animation. Typically application developers would use the App control which inherits from NavContainer.

samples.name: Scroll Container
samples.description: The Scroll Container is a control that can display arbitrary content within a limited screen area and provides touch scrolling to make all content accessible.

samples.name: Tile Container
samples.description: Tiles: a modern UI design pattern for overview & navigation.

samples.name: Panel
samples.description: Panels are helpful to group custom content. They can be decorated with header and info toolbars.

samples.name: Panel - Expand / Collapse
samples.description: Panels also have the possibility to expand/collapse their content (including the infoToolbar if available). [since rel. 1.22]

samples.name: PDF Viewer - Embedded
samples.description: A PDF viewer embedded in another control.

samples.name: PDF Viewer - Popup
samples.description: A PDF viewer opening as a popup dialog.

samples.name: PDF Viewer - Two PDF Documents
samples.description: Two PDF viewer frames displayed side by side.

samples.name: Flex Box - Opposing Alignment
samples.description: In this Flex Box the items are aligned at opposing ends of the container with justifyContent set to 'SpaceBetween'.

samples.name: Flex Box - Direction & Order
samples.description: You can influence the direction and order of elements in horizontal and vertical Flex Box controls with the direction property.

samples.name: Flex Box - Size Adjustments
samples.description: Automatic size adjustments can be achieved for Flex Items with the use of Flex Item Data settings on the contained controls.

samples.name: Flex Box - Basic Alignment
samples.description: Flex Box items can be placed in different areas using the justifyContent and alignItem properties.

samples.name: Flex Box - Equal Height Cols
samples.description: You can create balanced areas with Flex Box, such as these columns with equal height regardless of content.

samples.name: Flex Box - Navigation Examples
samples.description: Here is an example of how you can use navigation items as unordered list items in a Flex Box.

samples.name: Flex Box - Nested
samples.description: Flex Boxes can be nested. Remember also that HBox and VBox are 'convenience' controls based on the Flex Box control.

samples.name: Flex Box - Render Type
samples.description: Flex items can be rendered differently. By default, they are wrapped in a <div> element. Optionally, the bare controls can be rendered directly. This can affect the resulting layout.

samples.name: Formatted Text
samples.description: The control can be used for embedding formatted HTML text into your application.

samples.name: Page,Toolbar and Bar
samples.description: Each screen of a mobile application is typically represented by a 'Page' consisting of a header, a scrollable content area and optionally a footer. The standard header offers a navigation button and a title. Alternatively you can provide a customer header. Gernerally you should use Toolbars in the Page. If you need a centered title you may use a Bar.

samples.name: Fiori Object Page - Standard Classes
samples.description: This page implements the same sample as in 'Fiori Sample Page - sapUiFioriObjectPage' using standard margin classes. In contrast to using 'sapUiFioriObjectPage', the margins used for form, list, table and panel are responsive: they adapt to the available screen width. For more information, please search for 'Standard Margins' and take a look at our samples.

samples.name: Flexible sizing - Icon Tab Bar
samples.description: This page shows flexible sizing with an Icon Tab Bar: The upper part extends with its content, but doesn't react to viewport changes. The Icon Tab Bar reacts to the viewport size. The table inside takes the available space. If the minimum size of the table is reached, the page begins to scroll.

samples.name: Flexible sizing - Toolbar
samples.description: This page shows flexible sizing with a Toolbar. The upper part extends with its content, but doesn't react to viewport changes. The lower part reacts to the viewport size. The table inside takes the available space. If the minimum size of the table is reached, the page begins to scroll.

samples.name: Page Floating Footer
samples.description: The floating Footer allows the user to see the underlying content.

samples.name: Icon Tab Bar - Filter
samples.description: In this example, the Icon Tab Bar is used to apply filters on a table and display the count of the items for each view.

samples.name: Icon Tab Bar - Icons Only
samples.description: In this example, the Icon Tab Bar tabs display icons only.

samples.name: Icon Tab Bar - Text and Count
samples.description: In this example, the Icon Tab Bar tabs display text and corresponding count.

samples.name: Icon Tab Bar - Inline Mode
samples.description: In this example, the Icon Tab Bar tabs display the text and the count in one line.

samples.name: Icon Tab Bar - Process
samples.description: In this example, the Icon Tab Bar is used to apply filters on the same content along a business process.

samples.name: Icon Tab Bar - Text Only
samples.description: In this example, the Icon Tab Bar tabs display text only.

samples.name: Icon Tab Bar - Stretch Content Height
samples.description: In this example, the IconTabBar height is stretched to the maximum height of the page content. Note: The height of the parent container must be defined as a fixed value. Also, applyContentPadding property is set to false and backgroundDesign property is set to Transparent.

samples.name: Icon Tab - Separator
samples.description: This is an example how to use separators in the Icon Tab Bar. You can choose an icon as a separator or use the default vertical line.

samples.name: Icon Tab Bar - Overflow Select List
samples.description: In this example when some of the tab items are not visible, they are displayed in an overflow select list for easier selection.

samples.name: Icon Tab Bar - Background Design
samples.description: In this example the backgroundDesign and headerBackgroundDesign properties are demonstrated.

samples.name: Icon Tab Bar - Tabs drag and drop
samples.description: This example shows how the tab filters can be reordered with drag and drop. Works only on desktop devices.

samples.name: Icon Tab Bar - Tab Density Mode
samples.description: In this example, the Icon Tab Bar is used in different tab density modes.

samples.name: Busy Indicator
samples.description: The Busy Indicator signals that some operation is going on and that the user must wait. It does not block the current UI screen so other operations could be triggered in parallel.

samples.name: Image
samples.description: Images are faster than words and attract people's attention. Images can also have an active state or be used in SVG format.

samples.name: Image with ImageMode.Background
samples.description: Visualizes the state of the control when the mode property is set to ImageMode.Background.

samples.name: Feed Content
samples.description: Shows the tile containing the text of the feed, a subheader, and a numeric value.

samples.name: Label with Inputs
samples.description: Labels are helpful when you need to describe some other UI control.

samples.name: Label Properties
samples.description: This sample shows the different behaviors of a label.

samples.name: Progress Indicator
samples.description: Shows the progress of a process in a graphical way. To indicate the progress, the inside of the ProgressIndicator is filled with a color.

samples.name: Text
samples.description: The text control can be used for embedding longer paragraphs of text into your application, that need text wrapping.

samples.name: Text - Max Lines
samples.description: The Text control has a property to limit the number of lines for wrapping texts.

samples.name: Text - Render Whitespace
samples.description: The Text control has a property allowing browsers to render whitespace and tabs.

samples.name: Text - Hyphenation
samples.description: The Text control has a property allowing hyphenation.

samples.name: Title
samples.description: The Title control is a simple one line text with additional semantic information about the level of the following section in the page structure for accessibility purposes.

samples.name: Title Properties
samples.description: This sample shows the different behaviors of a title.

samples.name: Object Attribute
samples.description: This is an example of Object Attribute used standalone.

samples.name: Object Attribute inside Table
samples.description: This is an example of Object Attribute used inside Table.

samples.name: Object Header
samples.description: This is a Object Header which displays the basic information about objects similar to the Object List Item. Besides a title and number you can show multiple attributes (on the left) and statuses (on the right).

samples.name: Object Header  Active Attributes
samples.description: Active Object Attributes can trigger actions, such as navigating to related content inside or outside of the current application, or displaying additional information in a popover.

samples.name: Object Header - With Image
samples.description:
An Object Header will also make space for an image if one is specified, via a URL for the 'icon' property. 
Note: This example shows the image inside ObjectHeader with the responsive property set to false. On phone in portrait mode, the image remains visible.

samples.name: Object Header - With Circle-shaped Image
samples.description:
An Object Header can set shape of the image by using 'imageShape' property. The shapes could be Square (by default) and Circle. 
Note: This example shows the image inside ObjectHeader with the responsive property set to true. On phone in portrait mode, the image is hidden.

samples.name: Object Header - Favorite & Flag
samples.description:
The Object Header can indicate whether the object is a favorite, or has been flagged for further action. Changing these states is done elsewhere.

Note: The markFlagged and markFavorite properties are deprecated as of version 1.42. We recommend using the markers aggregation instead.

samples.name: Object Header - Select Title
samples.description: This is a Object Header with a title selection. This can be used to switch between variants of the business object being shown.

samples.name: Object Header - Active Title
samples.description: The Object Header's title can be active to trigger further actions like showing additional information in a Popover.

samples.name: Object Header - Condensed
samples.description: The Object Header is shown in condensed mode with title, number, number unit and one attribute.

samples.name: Object Header Responsive I
samples.description: This is a responsive Object Header with a Title, 2 Statuses/Attributes rendered next to the title in a fullScreenOptimized mode (fullScreenOptimized = true).

samples.name: Object Header Responsive II
samples.description: This is a responsive Object Header with a Title, 2 Statuses/Attributes rendered below the title in a Master/Detail mode (fullScreenOptimized = false).

samples.name: Object Header Responsive III
samples.description: This is a responsive Object Header with a Title, number, 6 Statuses/Attributes rendered in 4 columns in a fullScreenOptimized mode (fullScreenOptimized = true).

samples.name: Object Header Responsive IV
samples.description: This is a responsive Object Header with a Title, number, 6 Statuses/Attributes rendered in 3 columns in a Master/Detail mode (fullScreenOptimized = false).

samples.name: Object Header Responsive V
samples.description: This is a responsive Object Header without a number and with a Title, 3 Statuses/Attributes.

samples.name: Object Header - markers aggregation
samples.description: This sample shows the different states of an Object Header, which can be set using the markers.

samples.name: Object Identifier
samples.description: The object identifier is a small building block representing an object by a title and short description. Often it is used in the first column of a table.

samples.name: Object Marker in a table
samples.description: The ObjectMarker is a small building block representing an object by an icon or text and icon. Often it is used in a table.

samples.name: Object Number
samples.description: The object number is a small building block representing an important, numerical attribute of an object together with it's unit. Often it is used in the last column of a table.

samples.name: Object Status
samples.description: The object status is a small building block representing a status with a semantic color.

samples.name: Check Box
samples.description: Checkboxes allow users to select a subset of options. If you want to offer an off/on setting you should use the Switch control instead.

samples.name: Tri-State Check Box
samples.description: In this sample, the CheckBox reflects the selection states of its dependent input fields - selected, not selected, and partially selected.

samples.name: Date Picker
samples.description: The Date Picker is an extension of the Input control and is dedicated to Date.

samples.name: Date Picker Mass Editing Scenario
samples.description: Using calendar in a dialog for changing dates in mass editing scenario.

samples.name: Date Time Input
samples.description: The Date & Time Input control allows input of dates and times using date and time pickers. [Deprecated since 1.32.8]

samples.name: Date Time Picker
samples.description: With the DateTimePicker a Date can be entered or selected including the time part.

samples.name: Radio Button
samples.description: Typically the Radio Button is used by other controls. E.g. the List uses it for the single selection. But you can also use the Radio Buttons control directly, to allow selection of exactly one of multiple options.

samples.name: Radio Button Group
samples.description: A wrapper for a group of radio buttons.

samples.name: Rating Indicator
samples.description: A Rating Indicator can be used to both indicate and/or rate content.

samples.name: Segmented Button
samples.description: The Segmented Button allows the user to pick one out of many options for displaying the content of the current page. It is a UI pattern from iOS, now also available for other platforms. Putting the Segmented Button to a Bar control on non-iOS platforms will result in something very close to a tab.

samples.name: Segmented Button in View Settings Dialog
samples.description: Segmented Button used in View Settings Dialog component

samples.name: Segmented Button in Dialog
samples.description: Segmented Button used in Dialog component

samples.name: Segmented Button in Input List Item
samples.description: Segmented Button used in Input List Item component

samples.name: Select
samples.description: Illustrates the usage of a Select in header, footer and content of a page. Note the different display options.

samples.name: Select - Two columns layout
samples.description: Use the select dropdown list with two columns layout if you need to display additional information to your options, like e.g. currencies to countries or abbreviations to systems.

samples.name: Select - Validation states
samples.description: Visualizes the validation state of the control, for example, Error, Warning and Success.

samples.name: Select - Wrapping text
samples.description: Illustrates how the text in items wrap.

samples.name: Select - with icons
samples.description: Illustrates the usage of a Select with icons

samples.name: SelectList
samples.description: A SelectList allows the user to select one item from a list of choices.

samples.name: SelectList - with icons
samples.description: A SelectList with icons.

samples.name: Semantic Page Master-Detail
samples.description: Semantic Page Master/Detail

samples.name: Semantic Page Full Screen
samples.description: Semantic Page Full Screen

samples.name: Semantic Page using Draft Indicator
samples.description: Integration of Draft Indicator inside Semantic Page

samples.name: Semantic Page using Floating Footer
samples.description: Integration of Floating Footer inside Semantic Page

samples.name: Action Select
samples.description: Illustrates an Action Select with 2 actions.

samples.name: MultiComboBox
samples.description: Choose one or more out of multiple options with the MultiComboBox control.

samples.name: MultiComboBox - Filtering and Suggestions
samples.description: The default filtering is 'starts with per term', which filters by the beginning of every word in every column.

samples.name: MultiComboBox - Custom Filtering and Suggestions
samples.description: The default filtering for the suggestionsItems aggregation uses a 'starts with per term' style operator. You can override this with your own custom filter function using the setFilterFunction method.

samples.name: MultiComboBox - Grouping of items
samples.description: Items in the MultiComboBox could be grouped by a property

samples.name: MultiComboBox - Two columns layout
samples.description: Use the dropdown list with two columns layout if you need to display additional information to your options, like e.g. currencies to countries or abbreviations to systems.

samples.name: P13nDialog stand-alone
samples.description: Dialog for personalization of column order and their visibility.

samples.name: P13nDialog stand-alone
samples.description: Dialog for personalization of dimension/measure order and their visibility.

samples.name: MultiInput
samples.description: MultiInput provides functionality to add / remove / enter tokens.

samples.name: MultiInput Validators
samples.description: MultiInput uses validators to accept, decline and change tokens.

samples.name: MultiInput Filtering and Suggestions
samples.description: The default filtering is 'starts with per term', which filters by the beginning of every word in every column.

samples.name: MultiInput Custom Filtering
samples.description: The default filtering for the suggestionItems aggregation uses is a 'starts with per term' style operator. You can overwrite this with your own custom filter function using the Input control's setFilterFunction method.

samples.name: MultiInput Data Binding
samples.description: MultiInput data binding allows data to be bound to tokens in MultiInput.

samples.name: MultiInput with Max Tokens
samples.description: Number of Tokens in MultiInput cannot exceed the maxToken number.

samples.name: MultiInput tokenUpdate event example
samples.description: MultiInput fires several tokenUpdate events depending on when the tokens were validated.

samples.name: MultiInput - Grouping of items
samples.description: Items in the MultiInput could be grouped by a property

samples.name: MultiInput with Value Help
samples.description: MultiInput that includes a SelectDialog as a value help dialog

samples.name: Numeric Content of Different Colors
samples.description: Shows NumericContent including numbers, units of measurement, and status arrows indicating a trend. The numbers can be colored according to their meaning.

samples.name: Numeric Content with Icon
samples.description: Shows NumericContent including an icon.

samples.name: Numeric Content Without Margins
samples.description: This is an example of the NumericContent that contains no margins, so the control is aligned to the left and to the top without any margins.

samples.name: Tree - Basic
samples.description: Tree displays data in hierarchical structure.

samples.name: Tree - InitialExpand & CollapseAll
samples.description: This example shows the initial expand state and how to collapse all nodes.

samples.name: Tree - Drag and Drop
samples.description: This example shows drag-and-drop capability.

samples.name: Tree - Icon & Context Menu
samples.description: Tree item with icon. This example also shows the context menu for the items in the Tree control.

samples.name: Tree - Multi Expand & Collapse
samples.description: This example shows how to expand/collapse multiple nodes and demonstrates the sticky header toolbar and info toolbar options.

samples.name: Tree - Lazy loading with a JSON model
samples.description: Shows how lazy loading with a JSON model can be done using the toggleOpenState event.

samples.name: Tree - OData
samples.description: This example shows Tree with OData service.

samples.name: Tree - Selection
samples.description: This example shows different selection modes of Tree.

samples.name: RangeSlider
samples.description: With the RangeSlider a user can specify range from a numerical interval.

samples.name: Slider
samples.description: With the Slider a user can choose a value from a numerical range.

samples.name: Text Area
samples.description: The Text Area allows to enter multi-line text and automatically breaks to a new line for overflow text. If the text gets too big to be displayed at once the user can scroll up and down.

samples.name: TextArea with MaxLength = true
samples.description: Shows the behavior of the control with the new showExceededText property (since 1.48) and maxLength = true

samples.name: TextArea - Value Update
samples.description: Since 1.30 the value property of sap.m.TextArea is not updated on every keystroke, but first when the user presses Enter or leaves the input. The change was necessary to fully support the standard UI5 data binding with formatters and types. If you still need immediate update you have 2 options: Handle liveChange events or enable the boolean property valueLiveUpdate.

samples.name: TextArea - Growing
samples.description: Since 1.38 the growing property of sap.m.TextArea gives the ability of a control to automatically grow and shrink dynamically with its content.

samples.name: Switch
samples.description: "Some say it is only a switch, I say it is one of the most stylish controls in the universe of mobile UI controls." (unknown developer)

samples.name: Search Field
samples.description: Use the Search Field to let the user enter a search string and trigger the search process.

samples.name: Search Field - Suggestions
samples.description: Add suggestion capabilities to a basic Search Field.

samples.name: Dialog With Confirm Options
samples.description: Creating a dialog with confirm and reject options that replaces the confirmDialog functionality.

samples.name: List - Selection & Search
samples.description: When searching a list with multi selection the previously selected items will stay selected. This is managed by the list control for you.

samples.name: Facet Filter - Simple
samples.description: With the Facet Filter you can offer multiple filters ('facets') to assist the user in narrowing down the data in, say, a table. With this default 'Simple' type, each filter is displayed in a row for selection.

samples.name: Facet Filter - Light
samples.description: This is a 'Light' version of the Facet Filter. It is for small displays where only a selectable summary bar is shown, and a dialog is shown for setting the facet values.

samples.name: Input - Types
samples.description: Input type corresponds to the type attribute of the HTML input tag. On touch devices, it controls the keyboard layout. On desktop, the effect of this setting is browser dependent.

samples.name: Input - Password
samples.description: To make sure the password is not shown as clear text you set the 'type' of an input control to 'Password'.

samples.name: Input - Checked
samples.description: Input checks are handled via the validation of the data binding. In this example there are two inputs that are validated (a) while the user types and (b) when the user continues the process. If the built-in validation types are not sufficient you can create your own, like the email type in this example.

samples.name: Input - Assisted
samples.description: Assisted input is available via suggestions - shown as you type - and a value help dialog.

samples.name: Input - Assisted Two Values
samples.description: This example shows how to easily implement an assisted input with two-value suggestions.

samples.name: Input - Assisted Tabular Suggestions
samples.description: In this example assisted input is provided with table-like suggestions where several columns can display more details.

samples.name: Input - Suggestions - Dynamic
samples.description: With the Input control's suggest event, you can handle the suggestionItems yourself dynamically. This is useful when you have a server-side source of possible entries, and want to retrieve a specific subset by setting a filter on the aggregation binding with the model.

samples.name: Input - Suggestions - OSP
samples.description: If you need to use an Open Search Provider (OSP) to supply possible values, you can do this with the Input control's suggest event, and build the suggestionItems dynamically according to the results of the Open Search call.

samples.name: Input - Suggestions - Custom
samples.description: The default filtering for the suggestionItems aggregation uses a 'begins with' style operator. You can override this with your own custom filter function using the Input control's setFilterFunction method.

samples.name: Input - States
samples.description: This example demonstrates the different input field states, e.g. disabled, editable, with value help and value help only.

samples.name: Input - Value Update
samples.description: Since 1.24 the value property of sap.m.Input is not updated on every keystroke, but first when the user presses Enter or leaves the input. The change was necessary to fully support the standard UI5 data binding with formatters and types. If you still need immediate update you have 2 options: Handle liveChange events or enable the boolean property valueLiveUpdate.

samples.name: Input - Description
samples.description: This sample illustrates the usage of the description with input fields, e.g. description for units of measurements and currencies.

samples.name: Input - Key and Value
samples.description: This sample illustrates how the Input works with key and value values, when the data is available via list of suggestions.

samples.name: Input - Key and Value Tabular Suggestions
samples.description: This sample illustrates how the Input works with key and value values, when the data is provided with table-like suggestions.

samples.name: Input - Value States
samples.description: This example shows different input value states.

samples.name: Input - Grouping of items
samples.description: Items in the Input could be grouped by a property

samples.name: List - Header & Info Toolbar
samples.description: The 'headerText' property is an easy but limited way of setting the list header. If you need more flexibility you should assemble your own header or info toolbar that can also contain buttons. This example also demonstrates the sticky header toolbar and info toolbar options.

samples.name: List - No Data Indication
samples.description: If the list is empty it indicates this state by displaying a message text.

samples.name: List - Footer
samples.description: With the 'footerText' property you can set a message that is shown at the very end of the list.

samples.name: List - Selection
samples.description: 'Single selection' forces the user to choose exactly one out of many items. With the 'multi' selection the user can pick multiple items at the same time. This is helpful for e.g. batch processing. With 'includeItem' the selection is also changed when pressing the item.

samples.name: List - Items Type
samples.description: You can use the type property of any list item, which inherits from ListItemBase control, to demonstrate all possible types (see sap.m.ListType). In this example, you can see the Standard List Item behavior when different values of type property are selected.

samples.name: List - Deletion
samples.description: Setting 'Delete' mode on a List means you can trigger the deletion of single items with a single press. The application has to decide if an additional confirmation is required.

samples.name: List - Swipe
samples.description: With a swipe gesture you can show additional content for an item without having to navigate to a detail page. This feature is only available for touch devices.

samples.name: List - Growing
samples.description: The Growing feature helps if your content is too big to be loaded/shown at once. It paginates the content into smaller chunks - aka pages - which are loaded/shown one after another. Random access to pages (e.g jumping to the end) is not possible. Depending on the model the content is loaded on demand (OData) or shown on demand (JSON).

samples.name: List - Growing Upwards
samples.description: The Upwards Growing

samples.name: List - Grouping & Context Menu
samples.description: Grouping your items makes it easier for the user to browse and find the desired content. This example also shows the context menu for the items in the List control.

samples.name: List - Unread Indication
samples.description: With the Unread Indicator you can highlight new items making it easier for the user to discover them.

samples.name: List - Navigation Indication
samples.description: If only a subset of the list items are navigable you should indicate those by setting their 'type' to 'Navigation'. This displays an navigation arrow. Do not show arrows if all items are navigable. This achieved by setting the 'type' to 'Active'.

samples.name: List - Counter Indication
samples.description: The counter of an item quickly shows how many detail entries are related, without having to navigate to the detail page.

samples.name: List - Loading Indication
samples.description: You can use enableBusyIndicator property to display loading animation while the data is being loaded from server. By default, this property is true and busy indicator will be shown after 1000ms. This behavior can be customized by setting the busyIndicatorDelay property. When this property is set to false, items stay on the List until data loading is completed.

samples.name: Table - View Settings & Context Menu
samples.description: The View Settings Dialog is standard UI pattern for specifying sorting, grouping and filtering. For a table it should be triggered by a button in the table header with the 'drop-down-list' icon. The active filter should be shown with the table's info bar. This example also shows the context menu for the items in the Table control.

samples.name: Table - Fixed vs Auto Layout
samples.description:
You can use fixedLayout property to define the layout algorithm to be used for the table cells, rows, and columns.
When fixedLayout property is set to false, the width of the table and its cells depends on the content thereof. The column width is set by the widest unbreakable content in the cells.
By default, table is rendered with fixed layout algorithm. This means the horizontal layout only depends on the table's width and the width of the columns, not the contents of the cells. Cells in subsequent rows do not affect column widths.

samples.name: Table - Defining Column Width
samples.description: While defining the column width you can use percent values but you should be careful with them. Click to see some traps and tipps.

samples.name: Table - Alternate Row Colors
samples.description: Table with alternating light and dark background colors. Note: The effect of this feature is only visible in the SAP Belize and Belize Deep themes.

samples.name: Table - Drag and Drop
samples.description: Shows the different kinds of drag-and-drop capabilities across view boundaries along with custom context menu alternatives to perform these action.

samples.name: Table - Personalization
samples.description: The Table Perso Dialog is a simple dialog to be used for allowing the user to set table personalizations, specifically column visibility and order. Use the Table Perso Controller in conjunction with a persistence service based on the abstract Table Perso Provider to have changes made and persisted.

samples.name: Table - Merge Cells
samples.description:
With column duplicate merging, you can improve the display of repeated data. See the effect of mergeDuplicates on the Supplier column, space permitting.
Note: This feature is ignored if a column is shown in the pop-in.

samples.name: Table - Vertical Alignment
samples.description: This is a good example of how to vertically align different elements within a Table's ColumnListItem row template.

samples.name: Table - Outdated Data
samples.description: You can use the 'showOverlay' property to indicate that the table data is no longer up to date. When the user modifies the filter values of the table, this results in displaying an overlay, which disables operations on the table. Once the user chooses 'Search', the filter values and table data are synchronized again and the overlay is removed.

samples.name: Table - Breadcrumb
samples.description: With an InfoToolbar and some crumb logic you can navigate simple hierarchies with a breadcrumb table approach.

samples.name: Table - Export
samples.description: The table control provides export capabilities for downloading your data as a csv file. However, for huge tables, it is recommended that you provide an export mechanism on the server side.

samples.name: Table - Editable
samples.description: Table with edit/display togglable scenario.

samples.name: Table - ContextualWidth (Dynamic)
samples.description: This example shows the container-based pop-in behavior. The container has dynamic width.

samples.name: Table - ContextualWidth (Static)
samples.description: This example shows the container-based pop-in behavior. The container has static width.

samples.name: Table - Item Navigated
samples.description: This example demonstrates the navigated property of the item.

samples.name: Table - Data State Messages
samples.description: This example demonstrates how the DataStateIndicator plugin can be used to show binding-related errors for the table.

samples.name: Action List Item
samples.description: Use the Action List Item to trigger an action directly from a list

samples.name: Custom List Item
samples.description: With the Custom List Item you can add any kind of content to lists.

samples.name: Custom Tree Item
samples.description: With the Custom Tree Item you can add any kind of content to Tree.

samples.name: Display List Item

samples.name: Standard List Item - Adapt Title
samples.description: By default the title size adapts to the available space and gets bigger if the description is empty. List items with and without descriptions results in titles with different sizes. In this cases it is better to switch the size adaption off.

samples.name: Message Popover - Message Handling

samples.name: Message View inside Dialog

samples.name: Message View inside Popover
samples.description: A sample with Message View inside a Popover.

samples.description: A list item suitable for showing notifications to the user.

samples.description: A control suitable for grouping notifications. The sample uses JSON data bindings.

samples.name: Notification List Group with lazy loading of the notifications
samples.description: Notification List Group with lazy loading of the notifications.

samples.description: Notification List Group with max number of notifications reached. The group will render the max amount of notificatons, depending on device type allowed and then show a warning messge.

samples.name: Dialog
samples.description: Typically a Dialog prompts the user for decisions or additional information required by the application. The content of a dialog is fully customizable. If you want to highlight important information you should use the special type of 'Message Dialog'.

samples.name: Busy Dialog - Standard
samples.description: A Busy Dialog blocks the user interface until the currently running operation has been finished. No other activities can be started in parallel.

samples.name: Busy Dialog - Light
samples.description: This is a 'light' version of the standard Busy Dialog; it also blocks the user interface until the currently running operation has been finished. It has no UI components, so you must close it programmatically when appropriate.

samples.name: Placing a Title in OverflowToolbar/Toolbar
samples.description: The sap.m.Title control can be used to place a title inside an OverflowToolbar/Toolbar.

samples.name: Upload Collection - Instant Upload
samples.description: This control allows you to upload single or multiple files from their devices (desktop, tablet or smartphone) and attach them to the application immediately. The selection and upload process is completed in one step and is automatically triggered by the UploadCollection control.

samples.name: Upload Collection - Upload Pending
samples.description: You can use this UploadCollection scenario to select single or mutliple files and to add them to the upload list first. In a second step, the application can upload the selected files by calling the upload() function.

samples.name: With Download and Update Feature
samples.description: Shows the UploadCollection with a download and update version feature. If one item is selected, you can download it or update the item to a new version. Both features can only be used in the Instant Upload scenario.

samples.name: With Grouping, Sorting and Filtering Feature
samples.description: Shows the UploadCollection with grouping, sorting and filtering feature. After setting the criteria for filtering and sorting you get the filtering information displayed in the info toolbar.

samples.name: Upload Collection with Folder Hierarchy
samples.description: Shows the UploadCollection with a navigable folder structure.

samples.name: Upload Set

samples.name: Upload Set with Custom Uploader
samples.description: Shows how to customize the Upload Set control using a custom uploader.

samples.name: Margins All Around
samples.description: Use standard margin classes 'sapUiTinyMargin', 'sapUiSmallMargin', 'sapUiMediumMargin' or 'sapUiLargeMargin' to add a 8px (0.5rem), 16px (1rem), 32px (2rem) or 48px (3rem) margin to your control. This will clear the area all around your control (outside its border).

samples.name: Single-Sided Margins
samples.description: Clear the space to the left, right, top or bottom of your control. Choose a size ('Tiny', 'Small', 'Medium' or 'Large', which stands for 8px (0.5rem), 16px (1rem), 32px (2rem) or 48px (3rem) respectively) and a direction ('Begin', 'End', 'Top' or 'Bottom', where 'Begin' is left and 'End' is right and vice versa in right-to-left mode). If you would like to clear a 32px space to the left (resp. right in rtl mode), you would add class 'sapUiMediumMarginBegin'. You may also add several classes which have to point to different directions though, for example you would add classes 'sapUiLargeMarginEnd sapUiLargeMarginBottom' to clear a 48px space to the bottom and to the right (resp. to the left in rtl mode).

samples.name: Two-Sided Margins
samples.description: Clear the space to the left and right, top and bottom of your control. Choose a size ('Tiny', 'Small', 'Medium' or 'Large', which stands for 8px (0.5rem), 16px (1rem), 32px (2rem) or 48px (3rem) respectively) and an orientation ('BeginEnd', 'TopBottom'). If you would like to clear a 32px space to the left and right, you would add class 'sapUiMediumMarginBeginEnd'.

samples.name: Enforce Width 'auto'
samples.description: Some controls (for example the IconTabBar) do not have a 'width' property but still have a default width of 100%. We provide css class 'sapUiForceWidthAuto' to overwrite the control's width in such a case.

samples.name: Responsive Margins
samples.description: Clear the space around your control, where the margin depends on the device your are using.

samples.name: Collapsing Margins
samples.description: See how adjacent margins collapse to a single margin.

samples.name: Remove Margins
samples.description: Use our standard 'No-Margins' classes to remove existing margins from your control. You can either remove all margins at once or remove the margin on one or more sides.

samples.name: StepInput
samples.description: The StepInput allows the user to change stepwise a value by a predefined step and also to set additional description, such as units of measurement and currencies after the input field.

samples.name: Time Picker
samples.description:
TimePicker examples displaying the four time formats: 
HH : mm, 
HH : mm : ss, 
HH : mm : pp, 
HH : mm : ss : pp

samples.name: Time Picker Sliders
samples.description: TimePickerSliders used in a Dialog.

samples.name: No Container Content Padding

samples.name: Container Content Padding
samples.description: Apply the CSS class 'sapUiContentPadding' on a UI5 container control (e.g. Page, List, Dialog, Popover, ...) to add a default padding of 1rem (16px) around the container content area.

samples.name: Responsive Container Content Padding
samples.description: Apply the CSS class 'sapUiResponsiveContentPadding' on a UI5 container control (e.g. Page, List, Dialog, Popover, ...) to add a responsive padding based on the screen size around the container content area.

samples.name: Container Content Padding and Margins
samples.description: By combining the margin and padding concepts you can flexibly design your application layout without having to write any custom CSS. This example shows a HorizontalLayout that is layouted with the standard margin and padding classes provided by UI5.

samples.name: Overflow Toolbar - in a table and in the footer of a page
samples.description: Overflow Toolbar is useful for showing lists of action buttons that can display an icon in the toolbar, and icon+text when in the overflow.

samples.name: Wizard standard use case
samples.description: The Wizard is useful for breaking down complex tasks into smaller steps.

samples.name: Wizard branching use case

samples.name: Wizard edit mode
samples.description: Demonstrates the usage of the setCurrentStep association, which controlls the current step of the wizard. This association could be used to simulate 'edit mode' for the wizard by showing all steps in the wizard, without need from the user click next button on each of them.

samples.name: SplitApp standard use case
